TY  - JOUR
AU  - Forsythe, Robert
AU  - Lundholm, Russell
AU  - Rietz, Thomas
T1  - Cheap Talk, Fraud, and Adverse Selection in Financial Markets: Some Experimental Evidence
PY  - 1999
Y1  - 1999/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/revfin/12.3.0481
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
SP  - 481
EP  - 518
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We examine communication in laboratory games with asymmetric information. Sellers know true asset qualities. Potential buyers only know the quality distribution. Prohibiting communication, we document the degree of adverse selection. Then we examine two alternative communication mechanisms. Under “cheap talk”, each seller can announce any subset of qualities. Under “antifraud”, the subset must include the true quality. Both mechanisms improve market efficiency, but very differently. Relying on sellers' frequently exaggerated claims, buyers often overpay under cheap talk. Efficiency gains come at the buyer's expense. The antifraud rule improves efficiency further and eliminates the wealth transfer from buyers to sellers.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/revfin/12.3.0481
ER  - 



