TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kang, Jun-Koo
AU  - Kim, Yong-Cheol
AU  - Stulz, René M.
T1  - The Underreaction Hypothesis and the New Issue Puzzle: Evidence from Japan
PY  - 1999
Y1  - 1999/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/revfin/12.3.0519
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
SP  - 519
EP  - 534
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article investigates the long-term equity performance of Japanese firms issuing convertible debt and equity. We find that issuing firms perform poorly (except for equity rights issues) compared to nonissuing firms even though the stock-price reaction to convertible debt and equity issues is not negative for Japanese firms. This underperformance is strongest for firms issuing public convertible debt. In contrast to the United States, poor performance is not concentrated in smaller firms and in firms with a high market-to-book ratio. Simple behavioral explanations advanced for the new issue puzzle in the United States do not seem consistent with the Japanese experience.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/revfin/12.3.0519
ER  - 



